\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Social Engineering Attack Surfaces
\f1\b0 \'a0frame the human vulnerabilities as opposed to hardware or software vulnerabilities. Social engineering attackers use human psychology to exploit their victims to share sensitive information. An attacker don't have to go through the trouble of hacking into an organization's network if they can use social engineering to trick an employee into giving them access.\
\
The image below display the examples of social engineering attack surface.\
\
Phishing: is a type of social engineering attack where an attacker poses as a legititmate entity, such as a bank, government agency, or a well known company, to trick users into revealing sensitve inforation.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs30 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \cf0 \cb2 \strokec3 Spear-phishing
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 \'a0is a type of cyberattack that targets specific individuals or organizations typically through malicious emails. The goal of spear-phishing is to steal sensitive information such as login credentials or infect the targets' device with malware.\
\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Smishing\'a0
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 is a cyberattack that targets people through Short Message Service (SMS) or text messages. Smishing is often lucrative to attackers for credentials, banking information, and private data.\
\

\f0\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 Scareware\'a0
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF65539 is a cyberattack tactic that scares people into visiting spoofed or infected websites or downloading malicious software. This attack alerts the victim to a virus on their device, then tries to sell the victim a fake antivirus software that does nothing or turns out to be malware.\
\
