\fs32 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Perimeter-based network security models are no longer effective in today's world.\cb1 \
\ls10\ilvl0\cb2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 The internet has made data centers more accessible to attackers.\cb1 \
\ls10\ilvl0\cb2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 The distinction between internal and external networks is no longer clear.\cb1 \
\ls10\ilvl0\cb2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Insiders, cyberthreats, and stolen credentials can all pose a security risk.\cb1 \
\ls10\ilvl0\cb2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Traditional security devices and technologies are not effective at stopping all unwanted traffic.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs76\fsmilli38400 \cf0 \cb2 \strokec3 Emergence of the Zero Trust Model\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs40\fsmilli20400 \cf0 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa816\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf0 \cb2 \strokec3 A typical enterprise\'92s infrastructure has grown increasingly complex. A single enterprise may operate several internal networks, remote offices with their own local infrastructure, remote and/or mobile individuals, and cloud services. This complexity has outstripped legacy methods of perimeter-based network security as there is no single, easily identified perimeter for the enterprise. Perimeter-based network security has also been shown to be insufficient since once attackers breach the perimeter, further lateral movement is unhindered.\
This complex enterprise has led to the development of a new model for cybersecurity known as\'a0
\f0\b \cb2 \strokec3 Zero Trust (ZT)
\f1\b0 \cb2 \strokec3 . A ZT approach is primarily focused on data and service protection, but can be expanded to include all enterprise assets (devices, infrastructure components, applications, and virtual and cloud components) and subjects (end users, applications and other nonhuman entities that request information from resources).\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

